\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. A. unedo} L.,{\i  Sp. Pl.} 395 (1753). Usually a bushy shrub 1·5-3 m, occasionally a small tree up to 12 m. Bark fissured, peeling off in small flakes, mostly dull brown; young twigs glandular-setose, at least in part. Leaves 4-11 × 1·5-4 cm, oblong-lanceolate, usually 2-3 times as long as wide, serrate to subentire, glabrous except at extreme base; petiole 10 mm or less. Panicle 4-5 cm, drooping, appearing in autumn. Calyx 1·5 mm, with suborbicular lobes; corolla c. 9 × 7 mm, white, often tinged with green or pink. Berry c. 20 mm, covered with conical papillae, ripening through yellow and scarlet to deep crimson. 2n = 26.{\i  Evergreen scrub, wood-margins and rocky slopes. Mediterranean region and S. W. Europe, extending northwards locally to N.W. Ireland}. Al Bl Co Cr Ga Gr Hb Hs It Ju Lu Sa Si Tu.
\par 

